or noise and physiological fluctuations, we add controlled noise so the synthetic minute-level series is more realistic and models don’t overfit to overly clean patterns.\n","\n","Practical approach we’re following:\n","* We add noise **ONLY** to interpolated minutes to preserve ground truth and introduce plausible uncertainty rather than invent new events.\n","* We also use a ***per-dog noise scale*** because a single global noise level can under- or over-represent variability across dog.\n","\n","Methods:\n","\n","We chose **Autoregressive Model -  AR(1) + taper** and **Brownian Bridge** because they fit our key constraints: glucose has short-term “momentum,” and synthetic segments must remain consistent with observed endpoints.\n","\n","\n","* AR(1)+taper is the best default because it produces smooth, CGM-like fluctuations and avoids edge artifacts near observed points\n","* BB is the best comparison because it is endpoint-anchored by construction and provides a different, more random-walk-like within-gap shape"],"metadata":{"id":"zaTxkv4O3qfI"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### ⭐ Default Method: Autoregressive\n","\n","* Within each gap segment, we generate temporally correlated noise to capture short-term “momentum” (minute t depends on t-1).\n","* We also apply a taper so the noise is near zero at the segment endpoints (observed minutes).\n","* Each ID gets its own noise level (sigma)\n","* * We use ID rather than “dog” because our data is organized and modeled at the ID/segment level, and an individual dog may have slightly different dynamics between different monitoring period. This keeps the noise calibration aligned with the actual unit used in preprocessing and training.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"JzlAqFf8V1AE"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Step 1: Estimate per-dog noise level (sigma)**\n","\n","For each dog, we compute the ROC between consecutive observed points. And dogs with larger ROC variability are naturally \"wigglier\"."],"metadata":{"id":"jK0r_W_Ee10F"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["def estimate_sigma_by_id_from_roc(minute_canine, sigma_floor=0.8):\n","    \"\"\"\n","    Estimates dog-specific noise level by looking at how much\n","    their glucose 'Rate of Change' (ROC) varies.\n","    \"\"\"\n","    sigma_by_id = {}\n","\n","    for gid, group in minute_canine.groupby(\"ID\", sort=False):\n","        # 1. Filter to real observed data points\n","        obs = group[group[\"is_observed\"] == True].copy()\n","\n","        # 2. Calculate the Rate of Change (ROC) per minute\n","        dt = obs[\"timestamp\"].diff().dt.total_seconds() / 60.0\n","        dg = obs[\"observed_glucose\"].diff()\n","        roc = (dg / dt).dropna()\n","\n","        # 3. Sigma is the standard deviation of these normalized changes\n","        sigma = roc.std()\n","\n","        # Use the floor value to ensure a minimum amount of realistic variability\n","        sigma_by_id[gid] = max(sigma, sigma_floor)\n","\n","    return sigma_by_id"],"metadata":{"id":"q6ZIhWVnfbKd","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1774828792429,"user_tz":240,"elapsed":4,"user":{"displayName":"WooJung Kim","userId":"15923704063029269921"}}},"execution_count":19,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Per-dog sigma from observed ROC\n","sigma_by_id = estimate_sigma_by_id_from_roc(\n","    df_syn,\n","    sigma_floor=0.8,\n",")"],"metadata":{"id":"G2PWA_ihlP9h","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1774828801671,"user_tz":240,"elapsed":599,"user":{"displayName":"WooJung Kim","userId":"15923704063029269921"}}},"execution_count":20,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["print(sigma_by_id)\n","\n","print(\"dogs:\", len(sigma_by_id))\n","print(\"min/median/mean/max sigma:\", np.min(list(sigma_by_id.values())),\n","      np.median(list(sigma_by_id.values())),\n","      np.mean(list(sigma_by_id.values())),\n","      np.max(list(sigma_by_id.values())))"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"KkVNZe0wmj8Q",